<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 7:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2774a4c0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>7.</label.designator><headtext>Lay and Expert Opinion Testimony</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71fa1fc682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>7:13.</label.designator><headtext>Subjects of expert testimony—Vehicle speed</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Both expert and lay witnesses may give an opinion about the <page no="199"/>speed of a moving vehicle,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3e080e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] even though the witness made no speed estimate and formed no opinion at the time of observation.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0a7f07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A witness may base his opinion on seeing the vehicle headlights and hearing the noise of the motor,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0a7f17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] or on the sound of the motor alone.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0a7f27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Even if the witness had only “a glimpse” of the vehicle, he may state an opinion as to speed, and it should go to the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0a7f37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] In several Georgia cases, a lay witness gave an opinion about vehicle speed, without actually seeing the vehicle, based on factors that he observed at the vehicle.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0a7f47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>An expert may base his opinion on an examination of facts at the scene of a wreck.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0cf007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1970135188" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3b3e427fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Bartow County School Dist. v. Weaver</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0cf017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] an expert reconstructed a vehicle collision in his testimony before the jury.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1976135564" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3c01927fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Dual S. Enterprises, Inc. v. Webb</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3e0cf027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals reviewed the use of opinion testimony regarding speed in a case in which an expert witness testified about the “safe speed” for a truck to go around a curve, a lay witness testified about the collision point of impact based on factors he observed at the scene, <page no="200"/>and another expert witness testified about the point of impact based on his observations at the scene and, in part, upon measurements made by others.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic3e080e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1952104353" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a36d1727fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ellison v. Evans, 85 Ga. App. 292, 69 S.E.2d 94 (1952)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1985148580" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a36d1757fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ewing v. Johnston, 175 Ga. App. 760, 334 S.E.2d 703 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0a7f07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1928108530" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1a3746a27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Engle v. Finch, 37 Ga. App. 389, 140 S.E. 632 (1927)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1969133247" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3746a57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Horton v. State, 119 Ga. App. 43, 166 S.E.2d 47 (1969)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0a7f17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1949104411" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a37e2e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hill v. Kirk, 78 Ga. App. 310, 50 S.E.2d 785 (1948)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0a7f27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1941105167" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3831027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Murphy v. City of Atlanta, 64 Ga. App. 752, 14 S.E.2d 232 (1941)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0a7f37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1965126661" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a38a6327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Presley v. Griffith, 112 Ga. App. 377, 145 S.E.2d 384 (1965)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1976143343" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a38a6357fc011ea988285db8533e975">Gibbs v. Gianaris, 137 Ga. App. 18, 223 S.E.2d 4 (1975)</cite.query> (“brief second” to observe); <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1979127162" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a38a6387fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ferrell v. State, 149 Ga. App. 405, 254 S.E.2d 404 (1979)</cite.query> (a “glimpse”).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0a7f47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1928108530" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I1a3969827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Engle v. Finch, 37 Ga. App. 389, 140 S.E. 632 (1927)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1952104547" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3969857fc011ea988285db8533e975">Collins v. State, 86 Ga. App. 157, 71 S.E.2d 99 (1952)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1956125917" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3969887fc011ea988285db8533e975">Cobb v. Coleman, 94 Ga. App. 86, 93 S.E.2d 801 (1956)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1961126671" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a39698b7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Etheridge v. Hooper, 104 Ga. App. 227, 121 S.E.2d 323 (1961)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1962128625" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a39698e7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Central Container Corp. v. Westbrook, 105 Ga. App. 855, 126 S.E.2d 264 (1962)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1965125705" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3969917fc011ea988285db8533e975">Thornton v. Gaillard, 111 Ga. App. 371, 141 S.E.2d 771 (1965)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1966131751" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3969947fc011ea988285db8533e975">Jones v. Bradley, 113 Ga. App. 338, 147 S.E.2d 853 (1966)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0cf007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1966112876" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3a53e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Massey v. Stephens, 113 Ga. App. 10, 147 S.E.2d 53 (1966)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1966132171" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3a53e57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Jones v. State, 113 Ga. App. 667, 149 S.E.2d 426 (1966)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1969133944" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3a53e87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fried v. Richard, 119 Ga. App. 667, 168 S.E.2d 339 (1969)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1974128918" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3a53eb7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Finley v. Franklin Aluminum Co., 132 Ga. App. 70, 207 S.E.2d 543 (1974)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1975131912" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3a53ee7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hixson v. Barrow, 135 Ga. App. 519, 218 S.E.2d 253 (1975)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1978132124" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3a53f17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Harris v. Collins, 145 Ga. App. 827, 245 S.E.2d 13 (1978)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1970014027" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000108" ID="I1a3a53f37fc011ea988285db8533e975">Opinion testimony as to speed of motor vehicle based on skid marks and other facts, 29 A.L.R.3d 248</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0cf017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1970135188" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3b65527fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bartow County School Dist. v. Weaver, 121 Ga. App. 733, 175 S.E.2d 78 (1970)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3e0cf027fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1976135564" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3c4fb27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Dual S. Enterprises, Inc. v. Webb, 138 Ga. App. 810, 227 S.E.2d 418 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1987073801" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3cc4e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Whidby v. Columbine Carrier, Inc., 182 Ga. App. 638, 356 S.E.2d 709 (1987)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017120" w-serial-number="1990057372" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I1a3cc4e57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Pender v. Witcher, 194 Ga. App. 72, 389 S.E.2d 560 (1989)</cite.query>), it was erroneous for the trial judge to exclude the opinion of a police officer as to speed based on the degree of damage to both vehicles and the distance they traveled after the impact.<eos/><page no="200"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 7:13<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
